Let $a_{i,j}$ denote the number in the $i$th row and $j$th column.  We have that
\begin{align*}
a_{i,j} &= a_{i+1,j} + a_{i+1,j+1} \\
&= a_{i+2,j} + 2a_{i+2,j+1} + a_{i+2,j+2} \\
&= a_{i+3,j} + 3a_{i+3,j+1} + 3a_{i+3,j+2} + a_{i+3,j+3} \\
&\qquad \vdots \\
&= \binom{i}{0} a_{11,j} + \binom{i}{1} a_{11,j+1} + \binom{i}{2} a_{11,j+2} + \dots + \binom{i}{11-j} a_{11,11}.
\end{align*}In particular, $a_{1,1} = a_{11,11}.$

Now, let $s$ denote the sum of the entries in the bottom row.  Then the number in the top square is
\begin{align*}
a_{1,1} &= \binom{10}{0} a_{11,1} + \binom{10}{1} a_{11,2} + \dots + \binom{10}{10} a_{11,11} \\
&= \binom{10}{0} s + \binom{10}{1} (s - a_{11,1}) + \dots + \binom{10}{10} (s - a_{11,1} - a_{11,2} - \dots - a_{11,10}).
\end{align*}We want $a_{1,1}$ to be a multiple of 3.  This means
\[\binom{10}{0} s + \binom{10}{1} (s - a_{11,1}) + \dots + \binom{10}{10} (s - a_{11,1} - a_{11,2} - \dots - a_{11,10}) \equiv 0 \pmod{3}.\]Note that $\binom{10}{k}$ is divisible by 3 if $0 < k < 10.$  Therefore, we can simplify the above congruence to
\[s + \binom{10}{0} a_{11,1} \equiv 0 \pmod{3}.\]Since $s$ and $a_{11,1}$ are either 0 or 1, we have $s + a_{11,1} \equiv 0, 1, 2 \pmod{3}.$  Therefore, $s + a_{11,1}$ must be 0 or 3.  This means the number of valid distributions of 0's and 1's in the bottom row is $\boxed{2}.$

