If the ant moves to a vertex adjacent to the bottom vertex, then the ant will move to the bottom vertex in the next move. There are two such vertices, so the probability that the ant moves to vertex B in one move is $\frac{2}{12}=\frac{1}{6}$. If the ant moves to vertex A adjacent to one of the four vertices adjacent to the bottom vertex, then there are two adjacent vertices to the bottom vertex that the ant can move to in the next move, and there are four such vertices, so the probability that the ant moves to vertex B in two moves is $\frac{4}{12}\cdot\frac{2}{3}=\frac{2}{9}$. Therefore, the probability that the ant moves to vertex B in either one or two moves is $\frac{1}{6}+\frac{2}{9}=\boxed{\frac{5}{18}}$.

